    "OpenAI持续在AI能力边界进行探索"
  ],
  "translationStatus": "translated",
  "contentHash": "f1d62f7b3ff1d69bd658961610bf8cad241dea5a47f07e954a18d0d1f1cd9414",
  "comments": [
    {
      "id": 48866617,
      "commentKey": "hackernews-48866617",
      "parentId": 48863490,
      "author": "mNovak",
      "publishedAt": "2026-07-10T23:21:00.000Z",
      "level": 1,
      "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48866617",
      "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48866617",
      "textRawHtml": "Unrelated to the accomplishment or proof itself, but it's interesting how much of the prompt, even in this latest-and-greatest model, is spent essentially telling the model to actually solve the problem. Things like \"Reject status reports, vague optimism, and claims that an unproved global compatibility statement is 'routine'.\"<p>Also a lot prompt spent feeding it strategies, which feel like they should/will eventually be deduced by the model itself, not explicitly stated. That's not to take away from the outcome in any way; rather, it feels sort of like when you would prompt GPT 4, \"think through your answer step by step,\" as a sort of proto-chain of thought.</p>",
      "textZhHtml": "与成就或证明本身无关，但有趣的是，即使在这个最新、最伟大的模型中，提示的大部分内容也主要用于告诉模型实际解决问题。诸如“拒绝状态报告、模糊的乐观情绪以及声称未经证实的全球兼容性声明是‘例行公事’之类的事情。”<p>还花费了大量的时间来提供策略，感觉它们应该/最终会由模型本身推断出来，而不是明确说明。这并不是要以任何方式影响结果。相反，这感觉有点像当你提示 GPT 4 时，“一步一步思考你的答案”，作为一种原始思维链。</p>",
      "translationStatus": "translated",
      "contentHash": "011cbfde3505451ba6b72cf0cb5625fdd66cfafac365a53acfdfd09f55c19572",
      "children": [
        {
          "id": 48867836,
          "commentKey": "hackernews-48867836",
          "parentId": 48866617,
          "author": "futureshock",
          "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T02:02:19.000Z",
          "level": 2,
          "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48867836",
          "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48867836",
          "textRawHtml": "I think a lot of this has to do with the post-training these models normally get. They are designed to answer basic questions with straightforward and short summary answers. They have the capacity to reason deeply, but they are not biased towards that unless prompted. I think it's because LLMs  as they are in 2026 are both highly capable but also parlor tricks. They are not sentient, you just set them up with the context and then they roll downhill. You could reach a genuinely novel answer, but only with the right input. They have no will and depend on human guidance. They are both a marvel and a machine.",
          "textZhHtml": "我认为这很大程度上与这些模型通常接受的后期训练有关。它们旨在通过简单而简短的摘要答案来回答基本问题。他们有能力进行深入推理，但除非受到提示，否则他们不会对此产生偏见。我认为这是因为 2026 年的法学硕士不仅能力很强，而且也很会耍花招。它们没有感知能力，你只需给它们设置上下文，然后它们就会滚下山去。你可以得到一个真正新颖的答案，但前提是输入正确。他们没有意志，依赖人类的指导。它们既是奇迹，也是机器。",
          "translationStatus": "translated",
          "contentHash": "659d77c95bbc5acfed12a0eabe9f11a33c1bc9159f3fd6e1fcb96ddbff5f1001",
          "children": [
            {
              "id": 48869846,
              "commentKey": "hackernews-48869846",
              "parentId": 48867836,
              "author": "walrus01",
              "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T08:01:24.000Z",
              "level": 3,
              "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48869846",
              "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48869846",
              "textRawHtml": "Something I've noticed is that if you run Qwen 3.6 35B-A3B (Q8) with a low temperature of 0.4, and leave default reasoning turned on, it will spend quite a lot of time in reasoning/thinking mode. But often it does figure out how to solve something on its own by correcting itself within its reasoning loop before it outputs the final 'answer'.<p>If you watch the progress of the reasoning in llama-server while it's doing the thinking, you can track its progress. Sometimes the dead ends it goes down or things that it considers and then disregards are themselves something useful to re-prompt it with later, and send it 'rolling downhill', to use the metaphor of another commenter here, in another direction towards the same effort.</p><p>Putting 3.6 35B-A3B into a state that lets it spend a <i>lot</i> of time in its reasoning mode before outputting an answer is probably not something that a web based SaaS LLM would tolerate, because it would frustrate many of the non technical end users who want a LLM to spit out an answer <i>now</i>.</p>",
              "textZhHtml": "我注意到，如果您以较低的速度运行 Qwen 3.6 35B-A3B (Q8)温度为0.4，并且打开默认推理，它将花费相当多的时间在推理/思考模式下。但通常它确实会在输出最终“答案”之前通过在推理循环中纠正自身来弄清楚如何自行解决问题。<p>如果您在 llama-server 进行思考时观察其推理进度，您可以跟踪其进度。有时，它陷入的死胡同或它考虑然后忽视的事情本身就是有用的东西，可以在以后重新提示它，并将其发送到“滚下坡”，用这里另一位评论者的比喻，在另一个方向上进行同样的努力。</p><p>将 3.6 35B-A3B 置于一种状态，让它在输出答案之前花费<i>很多</i>时间在推理模式中，这可能不是一个简单的事情。基于网络的 SaaS LLM 可以容忍，因为它会让许多希望 LLM 现在就给出答案的非技术最终用户感到沮丧。</p>",
              "translationStatus": "translated",
              "contentHash": "6ad48408d3f045ef691768590e3303a6c5e835bec1491cfaf6a61b8ea3ac05d9",
              "children": [
                {
                  "id": 48871202,
                  "commentKey": "hackernews-48871202",
                  "parentId": 48869846,
                  "author": "DiabloD3",
                  "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T11:47:13.000Z",
                  "level": 4,
                  "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48871202",
                  "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48871202",
                  "textRawHtml": "You'd have less problems with 27B, btw.",
                  "textZhHtml": "顺便说一句，使用 27B 会遇到更少的问题。",
                  "translationStatus": "translated",
                  "contentHash": "2b80d1900d930616a281f90ec74c9b10b55464523d9f49d296d05a06e762e2cb",
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "id": 48876631,
                      "commentKey": "hackernews-48876631",
                      "parentId": 48871202,
                      "author": "walrus01",
                      "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T22:55:56.000Z",
                      "level": 5,
                      "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48876631",
                      "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48876631",
                      "textRawHtml": "I didn't mean so much that it was a problem, but actually in some projects for exploring what's possible, watching its \"thinking\" mode output at temp 0.4 is intentional and useful to take notes and begin exploring new directions. Sometimes it'll come up with something I hadn't thought of, perhaps it will go down that direction, perhaps it'll disregard it...",
                      "textZhHtml": "我的意思倒不是说这有什么问题，而是在一些探索可能性的项目中，观察它在温度0.4下“思考”模式的输出是有意为之的，这有助于做笔记并开始探索新方向。有时它会想出一些我没想到的东西，也许它会顺着那个方向深入，也许它会将其忽略……",
                      "translationStatus": "translated",
                      "contentHash": "56112ddee3f48156375c53ebc938e40b7e494f6efdb53b4c7348433641e86826",
                      "children": [],
                      "isDeleted": false
                    }
                  ],
                  "isDeleted": false
                }
              ],
              "isDeleted": false
            },
            {
              "id": 48869408,
              "commentKey": "hackernews-48869408",
              "parentId": 48867836,
              "author": "gb2d_hn",
              "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T06:41:26.000Z",
              "level": 3,
              "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48869408",
              "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48869408",
              "textRawHtml": "'roll down hill' is a good way of putting it. They don't have 'will', but that's as we want it I think. I think alignment is harder if they develop will. Without will they are still tools that feel like an exoskeleton rather than something that will control us.",
              "textZhHtml": "“滚下山”是一个很好的表达方式。他们没有“意愿”，但我认为这就是我们想要的。我认为如果他们培养意愿，协调就会更困难。如果没有意志，它们仍然是感觉像外骨骼的工具，而不是控制我们的东西。",
              "translationStatus": "translated",
              "contentHash": "a022aeb7b233bfdc4f73b67a86e010dc9ce6511c6b1fb2d1f985f5a8116334be",
              "children": [
                {
                  "id": 48869771,
                  "commentKey": "hackernews-48869771",
                  "parentId": 48869408,
                  "author": "singularity2001",
                  "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T07:49:49.000Z",
                  "level": 4,
                  "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48869771",
                  "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48869771",
                  "textRawHtml": "Agents have a state which will unfold as a plan, especially in planning mode. Why not call this 'will'?",
                  "textZhHtml": "代理具有将作为计划展开的状态，尤其是在计划模式下。为什么不称其为“意愿”？",
                  "translationStatus": "translated",
                  "contentHash": "8e3da7c7d219a23f65110a3738863e90e6cb177d23fe0d0a50a8527778566431",
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "id": 48878852,
                      "commentKey": "hackernews-48878852",
                      "parentId": 48869771,
                      "author": "gb2d_hn",
                      "publishedAt": "2026-07-12T06:29:15.000Z",
                      "level": 5,
                      "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48878852",
                      "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48878852",
                      "textRawHtml": "I think because without the initial prompt, they are only interpreting our will, and do not act under their own volition.",
                      "textZhHtml": "我认为这是因为如果没有初始提示词，它们只是在解读我们的意图，而不是出于自身意愿采取行动。",
                      "translationStatus": "translated",
                      "contentHash": "6a4a9195f60053087cec610004af24c1de2745a98008c85c860ee8cd55d1b6e9",
                      "children": [],
                      "isDeleted": false
                    }
                  ],
                  "isDeleted": false
                }
              ],
              "isDeleted": false
            },
            {
              "id": 48869955,
              "commentKey": "hackernews-48869955",
              "parentId": 48867836,
              "author": "DiscourseFan",
              "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T08:16:28.000Z",
              "level": 3,
              "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48869955",
              "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48869955",
              "textRawHtml": "Even Fable hallucinates. I had it tracking down some very obscure Ancient Greek inscriptions and the response just made up a translation/context for one inscription after \"looking it up.\" Now, it was still a very particular thing and I really had to get into the weeds to push it to that point, but who knows how many other gaps, near or far, it will happily skip over just for the sake of coherence. I think this is an issue more primarily with LLMs than sensory systems like Waymos or all the ML applied to industrial processes--that really only requires pattern recognition, often very impressive and subtle pattern recognition but its no different from an artist learning to tell the difference between Prussian blue and Navy blue or a Sommelier learning the fine distinctions between various regions of Bordeaux. Language has many more avenues and introduces inherent contradictions that do not always lend themselves to easy resolution. But there are no alternatives paths visible to the models, there is only ever the next word; stochastic, in the sense that the possibility space is open; deterministic, in the sense that the final response is always a necessary result of every token that came before it in their total sequence. Thus, any response is constantly in the work of erasing any possible alternative, slowly narrowing down what <i>can</i> be written. If contradictions in language necessarily involve interpretation, then the models will only ever choose one at a time, and for them, it will always be the right one. But anyone who understands the subtleties of language can tell you that when it comes to determining the truth of an indeterminate statement, there is never just <i>one</i> right answer; or, rather, the answer which is taken to be the \"right\" one depends on the possibility of its own reversal into falsehood, if any argument has to be made to justify it.",
              "textZhHtml": "就连寓言也会产生幻觉。我让它追踪一些非常晦涩的古希腊铭文，而响应只是在“查找”后为一个铭文提供了翻译/上下文。现在，这仍然是一件非常特殊的事情，我真的必须深入讨论才能将其推到这一点，但谁知道有多少其他差距，无论远近，它都会为了连贯性而高兴地跳过。我认为这主要是法学硕士的问题，而不是 Waymos 等感官系统或所有应用于工业流程的机器学习的问题——实际上只需要模式识别，通常是非常令人印象深刻和微妙的模式识别，但这与艺术家学习区分普鲁士蓝和海军蓝的区别，或者侍酒师学习波尔多各个地区之间的细微差别没有什么不同。语言有更多的途径，并引入了固有的矛盾，这些矛盾并不总是容易解决。但模型没有可见的替代路径，只有下一个词；随机的，即可能性空间是开放的；确定性，即最终响应始终是整个序列中位于其之前的每个标记的必然结果。因此，任何回应都在不断地消除任何可能的替代方案，慢慢地缩小<i>可以</i>可写的范围。如果语言中的矛盾必然涉及解释，那么模型一次只会选择一种解释，而对于它们来说，它永远是正确的。但任何理解语言微妙之处的人都可以告诉你，在确定不确定陈述的真实性时，永远不会只有<i>一个</i>正确答案；而是只有一个。或者更确切地说，如果必须提出任何论证来证明其合理性，那么被认为是“正确”的答案取决于其自身逆转为虚假的可能性。",
              "translationStatus": "translated",
              "contentHash": "f2cce912e84eb93d162ce2bc379e8a221e59f9b4053f11bf8b5df7bfaeb9a2a4",
              "children": [
                {
                  "id": 48871724,
                  "commentKey": "hackernews-48871724",
                  "parentId": 48869955,
                  "author": "HarHarVeryFunny",
                  "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T13:04:57.000Z",
                  "level": 4,
                  "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48871724",
                  "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48871724",
                  "textRawHtml": "Hallucination is fundamental to how LLMs work, and is mostly unrelated to how large or smart they are.<p>Everything that an LLM outputs is just a statistical language-based (no real grounding) prediction. Luckily with a model based on a large training set most common questions may elicit coherent responses from the training data, but you don't need to veer too far off into \"questions less asked\" territory to get responses based on training data mashups that amount to best guesses that are wrong, aka hallucinations. The unfortunate part of this is that as a user you may only catch this when asking a question about something you are already fairly knowledgeable about, then you give some pushback to the model and it cheerfully acknowledges \"you're right - I made that up\".</p>",
                  "textZhHtml": "幻觉是法学硕士工作方式的基础，并且与法学硕士的规模或聪明程度大多无关。<p>法学硕士输出的所有内容都只是基于统计语言（没有真正基础）的预测。幸运的是，使用基于大型训练集的模型，最常见的问题可能会从训练数据中引出连贯的响应，但您无需偏离太远进入“较少提出的问题”领域，即可根据训练数据混搭获得响应，这些响应相当于错误的最佳猜测，即幻觉。不幸的是，作为用户，您可能只有在询问有关您已经相当了解的问题时才会发现这一点，然后您对模型进行一些回击，它会愉快地承认“您是对的 - 这是我编的”。</p>",
                  "translationStatus": "translated",
                  "contentHash": "c211a299d1eac449f2eb454b3ee29bfd75df0533c29e8ef074e91a6a205bff3a",
                  "children": [],
                  "isDeleted": false
                },
                {
                  "id": 48871255,
                  "commentKey": "hackernews-48871255",
                  "parentId": 48869955,
                  "author": "trogdor",
                  "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T11:57:01.000Z",
                  "level": 4,
                  "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48871255",
                  "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48871255",
                  "textRawHtml": "&gt;Even Fable hallucinates<p>It’s in the name :)</p>",
                  "textZhHtml": "&gt;就连《寓言》也会产生幻觉<p>就在名字里:)</p>",
                  "translationStatus": "translated",
                  "contentHash": "9775c9597bb6d698e3ece1957d9550255f603de2b268d7d94436d4af5732910e",
                  "children": [],
                  "isDeleted": false
                }
              ],
              "isDeleted": false
            }
          ],
          "isDeleted": false
        },
        {
          "id": 48871483,
          "commentKey": "hackernews-48871483",
          "parentId": 48866617,
          "author": "HarHarVeryFunny",
          "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T12:32:44.000Z",
          "level": 2,
          "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48871483",
          "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48871483",
          "textRawHtml": "Yes, the prompt, and use of subagents is interesting. It could be characterized as tree of thoughts rather than \"think step by step\" chain of thoughts.<p>I see the need for this as coming down to two things:</p><p>1) LLMs are fundamentally prediction machines, and therefore ultimately will only do what they are prompted to do (and whatever that leads to). They may have been trained on, and/or have access to, all sorts of information that may be useful to solve a problem, but their predictive nature is to only use that information if explicitly prompted to, else it remains \"dark\" and inaccessible other than by luck. You're essentially having to tell the model \"solve this problem using techniques A, B &amp; C\", otherwise techniques A, B &amp; C will be off the radar unless the model already associates them to the problem.</p><p>2) The fundamental reason this sort of brute force tree-of-thoughts \"explore all avenues\" prompting is necessary, is because the model itself has no inherent curiosity to explore. Humans work differently. Our behavior is also prediction based, but we are also built for problem solving and continual exploration/learning via traits like curiosity (driven by prediction failure).</p><p>Problem solving via search can to some extent be prompted for, as here, or achieved via an external harness, but impasse resolution via curiosity, directed exploration and continual learning (if/when something new/unpredicted is encountered) is trickier. You can't usefully prompt a predictive model to \"be curious\" since that will only cause it to predict what a curious person would do, rather than the model being curious in reaction to the specific gaps in it's own knowledge.</p>",
          "textZhHtml": "是的，子代理的提示和使用很有趣。它可以被描述为思想树，而不是“一步一步思考”的思想链。<p>我认为这样做的必要性归结为两件事：</p><p>1) LLM 本质上是预测机器，因此最终只会做他们被提示做的事情（以及导致的任何结果）。他们可能已经接受过培训，和/或有权访问可能对解决问题有用的各种信息，但他们的预测本质是仅在明确提示的情况下使用该信息，否则它仍然是“黑暗”且无法访问，除非运气好。你本质上必须告诉模型“使用技术 A、B 和 C 来解决这个问题”，否则技术 A、B 和 C 将不会被关注，除非模型已经将它们与问题相关联。</p><p>2）这种“探索所有途径”提示的强力思维树的根本原因是必要的，因为模型本身没有内在的好奇心去探索。人类的工作方式不同。我们的行为也是基于预测的，但我们也是为了通过好奇心（由预测失败驱动）等特征来解决问题和持续探索/学习而构建的。</p><p>通过搜索解决问题在某种程度上可以被提示，就像这里一样，或者通过外部工具来实现，但通过好奇心、定向探索和持续学习（如果/当遇到新的/不可预测的东西时）解决僵局是比较棘手的。您无法有效地提示预测模型“保持好奇”，因为这只会导致它预测好奇的人会做什么，而不是模型对自身知识中的特定差距做出反应。</p>",
          "translationStatus": "translated",
          "contentHash": "652c6136e2a98f4c379b58cb7d2c5bf8cada8f38f672df302eccf72de26f0cd8",
          "children": [
            {
              "id": 48877113,
              "commentKey": "hackernews-48877113",
              "parentId": 48871483,
              "author": "famouswaffles",
              "publishedAt": "2026-07-12T00:20:37.000Z",
              "level": 3,
              "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48877113",
              "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48877113",
              "textRawHtml": "It might also be helpful more than 'necessary'. The 2 most notable solutions have come from open ai themselves, but most of the 'LLM solves open problem' category are from 3rd parties doing their own thing.<p>This one was pretty impressive in its own right (probably the most impressive outside these 2), and the prompt is concise and basic.</p><p><a href=\"https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/amateur-armed-with-chatgpt-vibe-maths-a-60-year-old-problem/\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/amateur-armed-wit...</a></p><p><a href=\"https://chatgpt.com/share/69dd1c83-b164-8385-bf2e-8533e9baba9c\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://chatgpt.com/share/69dd1c83-b164-8385-bf2e-8533e9baba...</a></p>",
              "textZhHtml": "这也可能比“必要”更有帮助。两个最著名的解决方案都来自开放人工智能本身，但大多数“LLM 解决开放问题”类别都来自第三方做自己的事情。<p>这个解决方案本身就非常令人印象深刻（可能是这两个解决方案之外最令人印象深刻的解决方案），而且提示简洁而基本。</p><p><a href=\"https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/amateur-armed-with-chatgpt-vibe-maths-a-60-year-old-problem/\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/amateur-armed-wit...</a></p><p><a href=\"https://chatgpt.com/share/69dd1c83-b164-8385-bf2e-8533e9baba9c\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://chatgpt.com/share/69dd1c83-b164-8385-bf2e-8533e9baba...</a></p>",
              "translationStatus": "translated",
              "contentHash": "67508a5178d0a7a74dc7dd2778d2dcf715a5c57843a38318044599b98223add0",
              "children": [],
              "isDeleted": false
            }
          ],
          "isDeleted": false
        },
        {
          "id": 48867084,
          "commentKey": "hackernews-48867084",
          "parentId": 48866617,
          "author": "kypro",
          "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T00:21:32.000Z",
          "level": 2,
          "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48867084",
          "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48867084",
          "textRawHtml": "I thought that too. The prompt is full of metaheuristics.<p>I remember a couple of years back when people were saying how prompt engineering was a skill, and reading this prompt kinda took me back to that.</p><p>Were I to guess, the reason the model couldn't do this itself is because most of the time, for most problems, a lot of this is bad advice.</p><p>In search optimisation you're often trading between time and quality. A very broad search will return very bad results for a long time. Where as a more depth oriented search with some heuristic will tend to return a pretty good result (if not optimal or close to optimal) quickly.</p><p>I'd assume models naturally want to find some middle ground there because that's the best thing to do most of the time, but for very difficult problems where a decent attempt isn't good enough you want a much broader search that doesn't have the time constraints. Much of the prompt seemed to be in that direction – really encouraging broadness of the search, preventing early convergence, and remove pressure of time constraints.</p>",
          "textZhHtml": "我也是这么想的。该提示充满了元启发式的内容。<p>我记得几年前，当人们说即时工程是一项技能时，阅读此提示让我想起了这一点。</p><p>如果我猜的话，模型本身无法做到这一点的原因是因为大多数时候，对于大多数问题，其中很多都是糟糕的建议。</p><p>在搜索优化中，您经常在时间和质量之间进行权衡。非常广泛的搜索将在很长一段时间内返回非常糟糕的结果。而带有一些启发式的更深度的搜索往往会很快返回一个相当好的结果（如果不是最佳或接近最佳）。</p><p>我假设模型自然希望在那里找到一些中间立场，因为这是大多数时候最好的事情，但对于非常困难的问题，如果一个像样的尝试不够好，你需要一个更广泛的搜索，没有时间限制。大部分提示似乎都是朝着这个方向——真正鼓励搜索的广泛性，防止过早的收敛，并消除时间限制的压力。</p>",
          "translationStatus": "translated",
          "contentHash": "b30850a20eea6269f14f48985d841356a9793c2fdefaa94076b313029b6957f3",
          "children": [
            {
              "id": 48867375,
              "commentKey": "hackernews-48867375",
              "parentId": 48867084,
              "author": "sudo_cowsay",
              "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T00:54:28.000Z",
              "level": 3,
              "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48867375",
              "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48867375",
              "textRawHtml": "Same. I remember something like using AI to optimize your prompt to that specific model helps a lot. I am currently trying it and can sort of see a difference (I think....).",
              "textZhHtml": "相同。我记得像使用人工智能来优化针对特定模型的提示有很大帮助。我目前正在尝试，并且可以看到差异（我认为......）。",
              "translationStatus": "translated",
              "contentHash": "1816282d8ec86ac4c98ded1c2bfb82ee94ba3d1c893d537ba51846cda1e8c535",
              "children": [],
              "isDeleted": false
            }
          ],
          "isDeleted": false
        },
        {
          "id": 48866993,
          "commentKey": "hackernews-48866993",
          "parentId": 48866617,
          "author": "rando1234",
          "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T00:08:41.000Z",
          "level": 2,
          "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48866993",
          "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48866993",
          "textRawHtml": "It's funny, I found exactly the same thing when I asked about P=NP. The models outright refused to attempt to solve it, claiming it was too hard. I had to really battle to get it to suggest some promising suggestions.",
          "textZhHtml": "有趣的是，当我询问 P=NP 时，我发现了完全相同的事情。模型完全拒绝尝试解决这个问题，声称它太难了。我必须真正努力才能让它提出一些有希望的建议。",
          "translationStatus": "translated",
          "contentHash": "f8e5c0a3966febe8d8eb2cc05cec819bbe4a754623edab1163d8fa233de10168",
          "children": [],
          "isDeleted": false
        },
        {
          "id": 48867658,
          "commentKey": "hackernews-48867658",
          "parentId": 48866617,
          "author": "scarmig",
          "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T01:35:28.000Z",
          "level": 2,
          "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48867658",
          "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48867658",
          "textRawHtml": "LLMs have basic reasoning and a whole lot of memorization. Through that basic reasoning and pruned search, combined with piles of compute, you can prove lots of things. But the memorization of human failure prunes that possibility, and you need to expend effort convincing the LLM not to prematurely prune based on previous human failure.",
          "textZhHtml": "法学硕士拥有基本的推理能力和大量的记忆能力。通过基本推理和修剪搜索，再加上大量计算，您可以证明很多事情。但是对人为失败的记忆会消除这种可能性，并且您需要花费精力说服法学硕士不要根据以前的人为失败过早地进行修剪。",
          "translationStatus": "translated",
          "contentHash": "095473a771fb412f2e95a333d832935f59634876c52f16e7e45796f57a5462e3",
          "children": [
            {
              "id": 48868016,
              "commentKey": "hackernews-48868016",
              "parentId": 48867658,
              "author": "riddlemethat",
              "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T02:25:39.000Z",
              "level": 3,
              "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48868016",
              "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48868016",
              "textRawHtml": "The current foundational models have basic reasoning with glimpses of brilliant reasoning.",
              "textZhHtml": "当前的基础模型具有基本的推理能力，也有一些精彩的推理能力。",
              "translationStatus": "translated",
              "contentHash": "011223c417981f82c10a01a4106589bea74cc4c7cae470990120ecb6f0e73f67",
              "children": [
                {
                  "id": 48869136,
                  "commentKey": "hackernews-48869136",
                  "parentId": 48868016,
                  "author": "krona",
                  "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T05:47:15.000Z",
                  "level": 4,
                  "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48869136",
                  "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48869136",
                  "textRawHtml": "LLMs have almost no fluid intelligence or capacity for abstract inductive reasoning, relying on crystallized intelligence for basically everything.",
                  "textZhHtml": "大语言模型几乎没有流体智力或抽象归纳推理能力，基本上所有任务都依赖晶体智力。",
                  "translationStatus": "translated",
                  "contentHash": "313ad9f952c43dac7382ff500f34da880151cd07e852d1b6595f9b8d6f06eb70",
                  "children": [
                    {
                      "id": 48869787,
                      "commentKey": "hackernews-48869787",
                      "parentId": 48869136,
                      "author": "singularity2001",
                      "publishedAt": "2026-07-11T07:51:50.000Z",
                      "level": 5,
                      "hnUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48869787",
                      "sourceUrl": "https://news.ycombinator.com/item?id=48869787",
                      "textRawHtml": "If anything their capability of abstract inductive reasoning is way beyond the average human given how much better LLMs are at solving math problems, it's the paradox that they can do complicated reasoning before they can do intuitive peep-pe-boo.",
                      "textZhHtml": "事实上，考虑到大型语言模型在解决数学问题上远超人类，它们的抽象归纳推理能力其实远超常人。这其中的悖论在于，它们还没学会直觉性的躲猫猫，却已经能进行复杂的推理了。",
                      "translationStatus": "translated",
                      "contentHash": "1f19409a4ee522a9edcca73dff131e7b507645d78009f14f0d93bf564967c923",
                      "children": [],
                      "isDeleted": false
                    }
